I nursed till 19 months. When starting out, I was frustrated with pulling out the cover and finding an appropriate chair with high arms. My kid got heavy and would nurse for thirty minutes each side. Later on, I didn't use a cover (he'd wave it like a flag while nursing, rendering it useless), but as he grew it'd be harder to hold him. If I couldn't find an appropriate seat, like if I was on a bench at the mall, I'd cross one leg over the other, jam my diaper bag on top, and put my arm under that to help support the baby's weight. He was 20 pounds by four months, so a big kid.

I used a repurposed bag. I threw in a changing pad, a small satchel with diapers and wipes, and a bag for 'me', with tampons, brushes, meds, my wallet, etc. I also had a ziploc with extra clothes for him, and early on in nursing, an extra shirt for me. The waterproof was important for blow outs. A few extra bags were nice for when I couldn't find a trashcan after changing diapers.

My husband liked the satchel with diapers and wipes, since it was smaller and not flowery like my big bag. It was easy to carry so he could grab the bag, the baby, and the pad and go change him (when possible, many men's rooms don't have changing tables). The satchel also made it easier to shift the contents to the hiking pack when we went for a hike, or to tuck under the stroller when we went for a walk in the mall.

A bag that fit under a stroller was nice. Many strollers are big, but not all, so a bag that fit under was great. I found early on that a bag attached to the stroller handles could tip the bag, spilling baby out on the ground, which resulted in mommy getting dirty looks from strangers and feeling very guilty, and a baby with a scraped face.
